<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The United States has the most powerful military and the biggest economy in the world.  Our movies and music are consumed across the globe. But at least according to one measure, the <a href="//www.socialprogressimperative.org/">Social Progress Index</a>, we come in 16th. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Should the United States care that it&#8217;s not No. 1 in social progress &#8212; based on measures like health, ecosystem sustainability, basic education and personal safety?<br />
<span id="more-144432"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In this <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/04/03/opinion/were-not-no-1-were-not-no-1.html">Opinion piece</a> at the top of the Times most-emailed list, the columnist Nicholas Kristof writes:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
We in the United States grow up celebrating ourselves as the worldâs most powerful nation, the worldâs richest nation, the worldâs freest and most blessed nation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sure, technically Norwegians may be wealthier per capita, and the Japanese may live longer, but the world watches the N.B.A., melts at Katy Perry, uses iPhones to post on Facebook, trembles at our aircraft carriers, and blames the C.I.A. for everything. Weâre No. 1!</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In some ways we indisputably are, but a major new ranking of livability in 132 countries puts the United States in a sobering 16th place. We underperform because our economic and military strengths donât translate into well-being for the average citizen.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the Social Progress Index, the United States excels in access to advanced education but ranks 70th in health, 69th in ecosystem sustainability, 39th in basic education, 34th in access to water and sanitation and 31st in personal safety. Even in access to cellphones and the Internet, the United States ranks a disappointing 23rd, partly because one American in five lacks Internet access.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs astonishing that for a country that has Silicon Valley, lack of access to information is a red flag,â notes Michael Green, executive director of the Social Progress Imperative, which oversees the index. The United States has done better at investing in drones than in children, and cuts in social services could fray the social fabric further.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This Social Progress Index ranks New Zealand No. 1, followed by Switzerland, Iceland and the Netherlands. All are somewhat poorer than America per capita, yet they appear to do a better job of meeting the needs of their people.
</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students:</strong> Read the entire article, then tell us &#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Should the United States care that it&#8217;s not No. 1 in overall social progress &#8212; based on measures like health, basic education and personal safety? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Do you think measures like the Social Progress Index have any validity? Do they say something accurate about quality of life in the United States and other nations? Or, are they not as useful as more traditional measures like <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2010/05/16/magazine/16GDP-t.html">gross domestic product</a>?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Do you think it&#8217;s fair to compare a country as large and diverse as the United States with much smaller countries like New Zealand and Switzerland?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; One of the things that the Social Progress Index emphasizes is access. So while the United States has some of the best schools and hospitals in the world, for example, not every American has access to these institutions.  How important is access? </p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students 13 and older</strong> are invited to comment below. Please use only your <strong>first name</strong>. For <a href="//www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/privacysummary.html">privacy policy</a> reasons, we will not publish student comments that include a last name.</p>
	</div>
